    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is Wingdings?</summary>
        <p>Wingdings is a series of dingbat fonts developed by Microsoft in 1990. Instead of standard letters and numbers, the font renders characters as various symbols, shapes, and icons. It was originally designed to allow users to easily insert high-quality graphics into early word processing documents without using extra memory.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How does a Wingdings translator work?</summary>
        <p>A translator uses a one-to-to-one character mapping system. It takes the standard English letters you type (like 'A' or 'B') and swaps them out for the Unicode symbols that visually match the corresponding icons in the Wingdings font (like a peace sign or a hand pointing). It functions like a simple substitution cipher.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why can't I copy and paste Wingdings everywhere?</summary>
        <p>If you type Wingdings in Microsoft Word and paste it into a website, it will often revert to regular letters. This is because the underlying text is still just normal letters; only the font styling was changed. Modern Wingdings translators solve this by converting the text into actual Unicode symbols that persist across platforms.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Did Wingdings predict 9/11 with the Q33 NY code?</summary>
        <p>No, this was a viral internet hoax. While typing "Q33 NY" in Wingdings does produce icons of an airplane, documents (often mistaken for buildings), a skull, and a Star of David, the combination of letters was entirely fabricated. No flight involved in the attacks was designated Q33.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why is Wingdings popular again?</summary>
        <p>Wingdings experienced a massive resurgence due to the 2015 indie video game Undertale, which features a secret character named W.D. Gaster who communicates exclusively in uppercase Wingdings. Fans heavily utilize translators to decode the game's hidden lore.</p>
      </details>

